42 dead in Mozambique | Watersense.co.za
u'2010-03-13 20:27 \xe2\x80\x93Maputo \xe2\x80\x93Mozambique\xe2\x80\x99s health ministry spokesperson says the country\xe2\x80\x99s cholera outbreak has now killed 42 people in the northern and central parts of the southern African country. Leonardo Chavane says the disease is spreading,with more than 2 600 cases of people who have contracted the highly contagious yet easily preventable infection this year. He said Saturday that the situation remains worrying as some provinces hit by cholera are now also affected by flooding,which is likely to spread the disease further. Earlier this year,seven people died in a riot sparked by false rumors that health staff were spreading cholera rather than fighting it. The wave of attacks on health centers caused by such rumors has died down. \xe2\x80\x93 AP \n Mozambique has suffered many droughts and floods over the past decade,while still recovering from years of civil war. The recent cholera outbreak adds to the problems that face this beautiful yet struggling country. In many Southern African countries water borne diseases such as cholera is a major problem as clean water is not readily available and people are left with no choice but to drink from less than fresh water sources. \n The problem is that with out water you cannot survive. Water must become the world\xe2\x80\x99s top priority and all countries including the poorest countries should put the task of protecting and securing fresh clean water above everything else as it is the key to all life and cannot be replaced with any alternatives. \n Water Rhapsody Conservation Systems specialise in saving water and our systems have been developed and perfected over the past 16 years. We have rainwater harvesting,grey water reuse,toilet multiflush and swimming pool backwash recycling systems which effectively conserve significant amounts of scarce water allowing one to become more independent of municipal water supplies which takes pressure off this vital resource as well as saving the user money on water bills. To see how our brilliant systems work click on our product demonstration link., gray water recycling  ', 'Mozambique | Cholera | Humans'
http://www.watersense.co.za/2010/03/14/42-dead-in-mozambique/

u" Nangayi Guyson, AfricaNews reporter in Kampala, Uganda \n About 41 people out of 2,601 reported cholera cases have been killed in the northern and central parts of Mozambique, the spokesperson of the country's health ministry, Leonardo Chavane said. Rift Valley Fever
Free State, South Africa
'-29.000000','26.000000',5,3588
RVF claims another life in FS: News24: South Africa: News
' Your location is picked up as outside of South Africa. \n Thousands of fans pushed to get into a World Cup warm-up match between Nigeria and North Korea which left 15 people injured. \n As more sportsmen get caught with their pants down, experts have warned that they need to learn how to avoid temptation. \n Bloemfontein - The number of people killed in the Free State since the outbreak of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) has risen to two, health officials said on Monday. "A total of 21 human... cases of Rift Valley Fever have been confirmed, all acquired in Free State, with two deaths," Deputy Minister of Health Molefi Sefularo said in a statement. The department said most of the cases followed direct contact with RVF-infected livestock. The human cases were farmers, veterinarians and farm workers. Sefularo said additional suspect cases were currently being tested. On Monday, agricultural officials in the Northern Cape announced they were awaiting RVF test results from four districts. "The Northern Cape provincial government has embarked upon an all-out-effort to foil the current outbreak of RVF," agriculture MEC Norman Shushu said in a statement. 33 dead lambs \nShushu said one farm in the Colesberg area reported a confirmed case of RVF with four cattle dead, out of 14 that took ill. Suspected cases had also emerged around farms near Richmond, Carnavon -where one reported 30 dead lambs - Prieska and Douglas where farmers had reported livestock mortalities. "Samples were collected and we are awaiting the results thereof." Shushu said the Northern Cape has had no confirmed human cases. A suspected case in Colesberg tested negative. Provincial veterinary services would update the Red Meat Producers Organisation in the Northern Cape and the National African Farmers\' Union on the sickness on Monday. The provincial agriculture and health departments would launch a public awareness campaign on RVF. Shushu urged farmers in the affected areas to immediately vaccinate their animals and avoid opening carcasses they suspected died from RVF. Heavy rainfall  ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Cows'

HM Community News Reports
6 Mar 2010
Rift Valley Fever
Free State, South Africa
'-29.000000','26.000000',5,3588
1 dies from Rift Valley Fever: News24: South Africa: News
' Your location is picked up as outside of South Africa. \n Thousands of fans pushed to get into a World Cup warm-up match between Nigeria and North Korea which left 15 people injured. \n As more sportsmen get caught with their pants down, experts have warned that they need to learn how to avoid temptation. \n Books Galore! Millions of books available at discounted prices! Fiction, thrillers, biographies,... \n Johannesburg - One human death and five further cases of Rift Valley Fever have been reported, the health department said on Saturday. Spokesperson Fidel Hadebe said five cases were confirmed in the Free State and one in the Northern Cape thus far. One person died from the illness in the Free State. "It started off as an animal problem... but it\'s been transferred to people... we advise the people in affected areas to minimise contact with animals as far as possible," Hadebe said. People can contract the illness when they are bitten by infected mosquitoes or came into contact with sick animals. No cases of human-to-human transmission were reported, Hadebe said. The department reacted to the illness in the "context of its normal outbreak response mechanisms", Hadebe said. It was liaising with the agriculture department as part of its response. According to the World Health Organisation\'s website the disease is characterised by a "feverish syndrome with sudden onset of flu-like fever, muscle pain, joint pain and headache". Rift Valley Fever reportedly affected at least 1 000 livestock since the outbreak in areas such as Brandfort, Soutpan and Wesselsbron in the Free State. Earlier this week reports indicated that the Bultfontein farmers\' union asked livestock brokers to stop all auctions in an attempt to curb the outbreak. The union wants to restrain the movement of livestock within the district in an effort to avoid a general quarantine of the area, after the first outbreak of rift valley fever in the Free State in 35 years. According to farmers many pregnant cows and ewes in the district have either aborted or died since the outbreak. The illness was identified for the first time in South Africa in the 1950s with another outbreak in the mid-1970s.  ', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'

Rift Valley Fever
Free State, South Africa
'-29.000000','26.000000',5,3588
Health on update of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) outbreak
' 60 people with Rift Valley Fever (RVF) and two deaths \n26 March 2010\n Eight more people have been infected with Rift Valley Fever (RVF), bringing the total to 60 of laboratory confirmed human cases since the first incident on 13 February 2010. The mortality rate remains the same at two.\n The National Institute of Communicable Disease (NICD) reported this morning that of the 60 cases of infected people, 51 cases and two deaths are from Free State, four in Eastern Cape and five in Northern Cape.\n Direct contact with RVF-infected livestock and or linked to farms with confirmed animal cases of RVF, remain the main risk factor for the infection. The human cases are farmers, veterinarians and farm workers. Additional suspect cases are currently being tested. ', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'

'-29.500000','22.000000',5,12176

'[ Speeches & statements ]\n 47 human cases of Rift Valley fever (RVF) and animal cases spread to North West \n24 March 2010\n As of this morning 24 March 2010, five more laboratory confirmed human cases of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) have been reported by the National Institute of Communicable Disease (NICD), bringing the total to 47 of people infected by RVF.\n Of the 47 laboratory confirmed cases, the NICD reported that 41 cases with two deaths are in Free State, three in Eastern Cape and three Northern Cape. 39 Rift Valley fever (RVF) human cases and two deaths
' 39 Rift Valley fever (RVF) human cases and two deaths \n19 March 2010\n Seven more human laboratory cases of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) have been confirmed by the National Institute of Communicable Diseases (NICD), increasing the number of infected people to 39.\n The RVF which has been confined to two provinces - Free State and Northern Cape - since the first human laboratory case was confirmed on 13 February 2010 has spread to the Eastern Cape province.\n Of the 39 cases, 34 are in Free State, three in Eastern Cape and two in Northern Cape. 441850

HM Community News Reports
16 Mar 2010
Rift Valley Fever
Middleburg, Free State, South Africa
'-30.049999','26.616667',5,12169
State veterinarians confirm Rift Valley Fever in Middleburg and ...
' State veterinarians confirm Rift Valley Fever in Middleburg and Hofmeyer \n16 March 2010\n State veterinarians in the Department of Agriculture and Rural Development have confirmed an outbreak of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) in the Middleburg and Hofmeyer areas where 20 lambs and 200 sheep have died respectively.\n Following this outbreak state veterinarians have visited the affected farms and their neighbours where more samples were taken and sheep and goats were vaccinated.\n A total of 5 935 pregnant ewes were vaccinated in the following commercial farms, Grootdam (1 675), Beaconsfiled (1 000), Blaauwskop (310), Hillston (500), Helpmaker (1 700), Fortuinplaas (600) and Wolwekop (150). A total of 353 sheep and 88 goats in Middleburg have commonage have been vaccinated while in Hofmeyer 154 sheep and 300 goats were vaccinated. Blanket vaccination will take place in Hofmeyer and Middleburg commonages, positive farms and contact farms. ', 'Middleburg, Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Sheep', 'Hofmeyer, Eastern Cape, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Sheep'
http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/2010/10031615351001.htm

Rift Valley Fever

'-29.000000','26.000000',5,3588
Farmers urged to vaccinate their livestock against insect borne ...
' Farmers urged to vaccinate their livestock against insect borne diseases \n1 March 2010\n The Northern Cape MEC for Agriculture, Land Reform and Rural Development Norman Shushu is urging farmers to vaccinate their livestock against insect-borne diseases especially Rift Valley fever.\n According to the World Health organisation (WHO), Rift Valley fever is a viral zoonois that primarily affects animals but also has the capacity to infect humans.\n Infection can cause severe disease in both animals and humans, leading to high rates of disease and death. The current heavy rainfalls are making it possible for the disease carrying mosquitoes to emerge and the only way to stop or limit the impact of an outbreak is for farmers to vaccinate their livestock before the outbreak to allow for a build-up of immunity. ', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'
http://www.info.gov.za/speeches/2010/10030116051004.htm

Eyewitness News: WC has first human case of Rift Valley Fever
u' WC has first human case of Rift Valley Fever \n has its first official human case of Rift Valley Fever. A state veterinarian that treated infected animals has now contracted the disease. Thousands of livestock across the country have already been infected with the viral disease. It can also be transmitted to humans and two deaths have been reported in the Free State \n where the initial outbreak was confirmed. Western Cape Health MEC Theuns Botha said the chances of the disease spreading were high as winter approached. He added the patient had been quarantined. \xe2\x80\x9cThe vet that did an autopsy on an animal carcass in Beaufort West, has got all the symptoms that indicate that he contracted the infection,\xe2\x80\x9d said Botha. \n \xc2\xa0 \n How were you involved or affected? *  ', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans'

Rift Valley Fever - A total of 21 cases have been confirmed
' Rift Valley Fever - A total of 21 cases have been confirmed \nIssued by National Ministry of Health \n15 March 2010 \nAs of 15 March 2010, a total of 21 human laboratory confirmed cases of River Valley Fever (RVF) have been confirmed - all acquired in Free State - with two deaths. This brings a total to 22 human cases of RVF - with one in Northern Cape. \nMost of these cases reported direct contact with RVF-infected livestock and or linked to farms with confirmed animal cases of RVF. The human cases are; farmers, veterinarians and farm workers. Additional suspect cases are currently being tested. u" Readership of The Citizen's fibre edition has increased by 15% in the last year. \n Three more people infected with Rift Valley Fever \n JOHANNESBURG - Three more people have been infected with Rift Valley Fever (RVF), the ministry of health said on Wednesday. \n Spokeswoman Charity Bhengu said this brought the number of confirmed human laboratory cases to 69, while two people, both from the Free State, have died from the disease since the first incident was reported on February 13. \n \xe2\x80\x9cThe National Institute of Communicable Disease reported this (Wednesday) morning that of the 69 cases of infected people, 58 cases and two deaths are from Free State, four in Eastern Cape and seven in Northern Cape,\xe2\x80\x9d said Bhengu. Roll-out in fight against Rift Valley Feve - Cape Times
' Roll-out in fight against Rift Valley Fever \n The provincial agriculture department is implementing preventative measures to protect the Western Cape from Rift Valley Fever, a viral disease that affects humans and most animals, but not birds. \nSome 10 000 doses of live vaccine procured from Onderstepoort Biological Products are being distributed to high-risk areas to protect sheep and cattle in the province. \nAgriculture and Rural Development Minister Gerrit van Rensburg said the department was vaccinating animals in the Murraysburg area. \nFarmers have been advised to keep their stock away from areas with high mosquito activity.  ', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)'

' SA Meat Imports Banned Rift Valley Fever Alarm \n THE Ministry of Agriculture has banned with immediate effect imports of live animals that are ruminants from South Africa, as well as meat and meat products of domestic and wild ruminants. \nThe ban was necessitated by an outbreak of Rift Valley Fever (RVF) in several parts of South Africa recently, which caused the death of at least one person. \n"The ban will be in place until further notice," Dr Cleophas Bamhare, Acting Chief Veterinary Officer said yesterday. \n "No veterinary permits will be issued for imports of live ruminants, meat and meat products of domestic and wild ruminants originating from any part of South Africa. Rift Valley Fever in South Africa
u' Hay un brote de infecci\xf3n por virus de la FVR que est\xe1 afectando al ganado ovino, caprino y bovino, as\xed como a animales salvajes, en granjas de las provincias de Free State, Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Western Cape, Mpumalanga, North West y Gauteng. Hasta el 29 de marzo de 2010 se hab\xedan notificado casos confirmados mediante pruebas de laboratorio en animales de aproximadamente 78 granjas. La mortalidad del ganado ha sido alta (v\xe9ase el enlace que figura m\xe1s adelante).  Los Departamentos de Salud y de Agricultura, Silvicultura y Pescas est\xe1n investigando el brote con el apoyo del Instituto Nacional de Enfermedades Transmisibles y el Programa Sudafricano de Formaci\xf3n en Epidemiolog\xeda de Campo. Los Departamentos de Salud y de Agricultura est\xe1n tomando medidas para intensificar la vigilancia de la enfermedad en el ganado y controlar el brote.  En los \xfaltimos a\xf1os se han documentado en Sud\xe1frica casos espor\xe1dicos de FVR en los animales. El \xfaltimo brote importante en el ser humano se registr\xf3 en 1974-1976, cuando se vieron afectados unos 10\xa0000 a 20\xa0000 casos. San Antonio - Llaman a estar alertas sobre plagas de insectos y ...
u' Martes 30 de Marzo de 2010 \n San Antonio - Llaman a estar alertas sobre plagas de insectos y roedores \n El Departamento de Medio Ambiente de la Municipalidad de San Antonio llam\xc3\xb3 a toda la comunidad a mantenerse alerta frente al brote de diferentes plagas de insectos y otros que afloran con mucha m\xc3\xa1s fuerza luego de un movimiento tel\xc3\xbarico de la magnitud del que afect\xc3\xb3 a nuestro pa\xc3\xads el pasado 27 de febrero. \xa0\xa0La encargada del departamento, Rosa Mar\xc3\xada Romera, llam\xc3\xb3 a la comunidad a acercarse las oficinas de Medio Ambiente para recibir asistencia profesional frente a temas de erradicaci\xc3\xb3n de plagas. \xa0Luego de un movimiento tel\xc3\xbarico de esta magnitud, no s\xc3\xb3lo las construcciones se sacuden, en ocasiones hasta caer, sino que adem\xc3\xa1s una serie de plagas de insectos brotan de la tierra para invadir las casas de las personas. Piojos, pulgas, garrapatas, incluso sarna, brotan desde las profundidades de la tierra para invadir nuestros hogares. \xa0Frente a este problema, la jefe del Departamento de Medio Ambiente, Rosa Mar\xc3\xada Romero, llam\xc3\xb3 a la comunidad a desinfectar muy bien sus hogares para erradicar as\xc3\xad este tipo de plagas, que muchas veces atacan con m\xc3\xa1s fuerza a los m\xc3\xa1s peque\xc3\xb1os de la casa. \xa0Otro tipo de plagas que tambi\xc3\xa9n afloran luego de un sismo como este son los ratones y murci\xc3\xa9lagos, animales que por el mismo movimiento tel\xc3\xbarico reaccionan en forma m\xc3\xa1s activa, provoc\xc3\xa1ndole m\xc3\xa1s de un problema a los due\xc3\xb1os del inmueble invadido. \xa0En lo que se refiere a los roedores, Ana Mar\xc3\xada Romero, se\xc3\xb1al\xc3\xb3 que en el departamento de Medio Ambiente, por un baj\xc3\xadsimo costo se realizan las desratizaciones completas de un hogar, liberando as\xc3\xad a sus ocupantes de esta molesta plaga. \xa0En el caso de los murci\xc3\xa9lagos, este es un tema un poco m\xc3\xa1s delicado, ya que esta especie est\xc3\xa1 protegida y no se le puede da\xc3\xb1ar a menos que represente un peligro para las personas, situaci\xc3\xb3n que no se da con frecuencia. \xa0Rosa Mar\xc3\xada Romera, entreg\xc3\xb3 algunos consejos a los sanantoninos que tengan como hu\xc3\xa9sped a estos mam\xc3\xadferos voladores, ya que es normal que estos comi\xc3\xa9ncen a moverse llegado el ocaso, momento en el que salen a cazar insectos. \xa0La dificultad seg\xc3\xban la jefa de Medio Ambiente se genera cuando estos murci\xc3\xa9lagos comienzan a salir a plena luz del d\xc3\xada, esto seg\xc3\xban Romero indica que tienen alguna enfermedad, la cual puede ser transmitida a perros o gatos cercanos a la poblaci\xc3\xb3n donde est\xc3\xa1n. \xa0En este caso el consejo es llamar en forma inmediata al departamento de Medio Ambiente de la Municipalidad, para que estos profesionales capturen a los animalitos y los env\xc3\xaden a an\xc3\xa1lisis, de salir positivas las muestras frente a alguna enfermedad, se toman medidas de contenci\xc3\xb3n. \xa0Estas medidas antes se\xc3\xb1aladas corresponden a la vacunaci\xc3\xb3n de todos los animales dom\xc3\xa9sticos que residen a 200 metros a la redonda de donde fue encontrado el animal enfermo, adem\xc3\xa1s de que se realiza un operativo para buscar m\xc3\xa1s ejemplares de la especie infectada. \xa0Todo este trabajo corre por parte del departamento de Medio Ambiente de la Municipalidad, que se encarga de todo aquello que tiene que ver con la vacunaci\xc3\xb3n animal y la erradicaci\xc3\xb3n de la plaga que pone en peligro la salud de los habitantes de la zona. \xa0Otra de las noticias que Ana Mar\xc3\xada Romero entreg\xc3\xb3 a la comunidad tiene que ver con la vuelta de las esterilizaciones caninas que se realizaban hasta antes del terremoto, los interesados s\xc3\xb3lo deben dirigirse a las nuevas dependencias del departamento, ubicadas en Sanfuentes 2032, para tomar un hora y por una baj\xc3\xadsima suma de dinero operar a su perrita. \xa0Hay que recordar que este tipo de operaciones son bastante costosas y que en el caso del departamento de Medio Ambiente de la Municipalidad la realizan por cerca del 5% o 10% de lo que cuesta realizarlas en instituciones particulares y con los mismos est\xc3\xa1ndares profesionales. \n Capitan\xc3\xada de Puerto advierte sobre alerta de marejadas  ', 'Chile | Pests | Humans'

Valley Fever Rift in South Africa
u' Une \xe9pid\xe9mie d\u2019infections par le virus de la FVR, touchant les moutons, les ch\xe8vres, les bovins et les animaux sauvages, s\xe9vit actuellement dans les provinces de l\u2019\xc9tat-Libre, du Cap-Oriental, du Cap-du-Nord, du Cap-Occidental, de Mpumalanga, du Nord-Ouest et de Gauteng. Au 29 mars 2010, environ 78 \xe9levages avaient notifi\xe9 des cas confirm\xe9s par le laboratoire dans leur cheptel, avec une mortalit\xe9 importante. (Voir lien ci-dessous). Les investigations sur la flamb\xe9e, men\xe9es par le Minist\xe8re de la Sant\xe9 et le Minist\xe8re de l\u2019Agriculture, des For\xeats et des P\xeaches, sont en cours et sont soutenues par le Programme sud-africain de formation et d\u2019\xe9pid\xe9miologie sur le terrain (SA-FELTP) et le NICD. Les minist\xe8res de la sant\xe9 et de l\u2019agriculture prennent des mesures pour renforcer la surveillance dans les \xe9levages et g\xe9rer la lutte contre la flamb\xe9e. On a document\xe9 ces derni\xe8res ann\xe9es des cas sporadiques de FVR en Afrique du Sud. La derni\xe8re grande flamb\xe9e chez l\u2019homme a s\xe9vi de 1974 \xe0 1976 avec, selon les estimations, de 10 000 \xe0 20 000 cas d\u2019infection.Pour en savoir plus : The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)   Office International des \xc9pizooties (OIE)    ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Mpumalanga Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)'

'43.100903','-75.232666',5,11194
Person diagnosed with whooping cough attended state tournament
u'UTICA \xe2\x80\x94 The New York State Department of Health, Bureau of Immunization said in a release that it has been notified that a person diagnosed with pertussis, also known as whooping cough, attended the New York State Public High School Athletic Association Ice Hockey championships at the Utica Memorial Auditorium and spectators might have come into close contact with the individual and should be treated for symptoms. \n The event took place at the Aud between the dates of March 12-14, specifically on the dates March 12-13, and symptoms of pertussis usually develop 7 to 10 days after exposure, but can develop form 5 to 21 days after exposure and include a severe cough. If untreated, a person can transmit pertussis from onset of symptoms to three weeks after the onset of coughing episodes. \n Pertussis is a highly contagious disease involving the respiratory tract. It is caused by a bacterium that is found in the mouth, nose and throat of an infected person.  ', 'Utica, New York, United States | Whooping Cough | Humans'

World Health Organization
30 Mar 2010
Rift Valley Fever
South Africa
'-28.998529','25.092541',5,179
Rift Valley fever in South Africa
' There is an ongoing outbreak of Rift Valley Fever Virus (RVFV) infection affecting sheep, goats, cattle and wildlife on farms within Free State, Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Western Cape, Mpumalanga, North West, Gauteng provinces. As of 29 March 2010, approximately 78 farms reported laboratory-confirmed animal cases, with extensive livestock deaths. (see link below)  Outbreak investigations by the Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries are ongoing, and are being supported by the South African Field Epidemiology and Training Programme (SA-FELTP) and NICD. The Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture are taking measures to enhance disease surveillance among cattle and in managing the control of the disease outbreak.  Sporadic cases of RVF infection in animals have been documented in South Africa in recent years. The last major outbreak of the disease in humans occurred between 1974-76, where an estimated 10,000 to 20,000 cases were affected.For more information The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)   World organisation for animal health (OIE)    ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Mpumalanga Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Gauteng Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'North West Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)'

Rift Valley fever in South Africa
' There is an ongoing outbreak of Rift Valley Fever Virus (RVFV) infection affecting sheep, goats, cattle and wildlife on farms within Free State, Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Western Cape, Mpumalanga, North West, Gauteng provinces. As of 29 March 2010, approximately 78 farms reported laboratory-confirmed animal cases, with extensive livestock deaths. (see link below)  Outbreak investigations by the Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries are ongoing, and are being supported by the South African Field Epidemiology and Training Programme (SA-FELTP) and NICD. The Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture are taking measures to enhance disease surveillance among cattle and in managing the control of the disease outbreak.  Sporadic cases of RVF infection in animals have been documented in South Africa in recent years. ' There is an ongoing outbreak of Rift Valley Fever Virus (RVFV) infection affecting sheep, goats, cattle and wildlife on farms within Free State, Eastern Cape, Northern Cape, Western Cape, Mpumalanga, North West, Gauteng provinces. (see link below)  Outbreak investigations by the Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries are ongoing, and are being supported by the South African Field Epidemiology and Training Programme (SA-FELTP) and NICD. The Department of Health and the Department of Agriculture are taking measures to enhance disease surveillance among cattle and in managing the control of the disease outbreak.  Sporadic cases of RVF infection in animals have been documented in South Africa in recent years. The last major outbreak of the disease in humans occurred between 1974-76, where an estimated 10,000 to 20,000 cases were affected.For more information The National Institute for Communicable Diseases (NICD)   World organisation for animal health (OIE)    ', 'South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Northern Cape Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Eastern Cape Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Humans', 'Mpumalanga Region, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Gauteng Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'Free State, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)', 'North West Province, South Africa | Rift Valley Fever | Livestock (domestic)'

' The first case was announced on 28 March and is a 30 year-old female from Damietta district, Damietta Governorate. He died on 24 March.  Investigations into the source of infection indicated that both cases had exposure to sick and dead poultry. Congo RDC: Six cas suspects de fi\u00e8vre h\u00e9morragique signal\u00e9s dans la ...
u" Six cas suspects de fi\xc3\xa8vre h\xc3\xa9morragique signal\xc3\xa9s dans la province Orientale \n Six cas suspects de fi\xc3\xa8vre h\xc3\xa9morragique ont \xc3\xa9t\xc3\xa9 enregistr\xc3\xa9s du 2 au 14 mars dans la zone de sant\xc3\xa9 de Kitule, \xc3\xa0 135 km au Sud de Buta, dans la province Orientale au nord-est de la R\xc3\xa9publique d\xc3\xa9mocratique du Congo (RDC). \n Selon Bienvenue Apatala, m\xc3\xa9decin de zone de sant\xc3\xa9 de Kitule, qui a confirm\xc3\xa9 jeudi cette information, a fait savoir que 3 de 6 malades sont d\xc3\xa9c\xc3\xa9d\xc3\xa9s, tandis que 3 autres sont intern\xc3\xa9s dans un centre hospitalier le plus proche. Le virus causal de cette maladie n'a pas encore \xc3\xa9t\xc3\xa9 connu jusqu'\xc3\xa0 pr\xc3\xa9sent. Cependant, tous ces malades pr\xc3\xa9sentent les m\xc3\xaame signes : fortes fi\xc3\xa8vres et des vomissements accompagn\xc3\xa9s du sang. Des \xc3\xa9chantillons de sang pr\xc3\xa9lev\xc3\xa9s sur les malades ont \xc3\xa9t\xc3\xa9 envoy\xc3\xa9s \xc3\xa0 Kinshasa pour des examens appropri\xc3\xa9s. Cette maladie, dont les sympt\xc3\xb4mes s'apparentent \xc3\xa0 la fi\xc3\xa8vre h\xc3\xa9morragique \xc3\xa0 virus Ebola, cr\xc3\xa9e une panique au sein de la population de cette contr\xc3\xa9e. La fi\xc3\xa8vre h\xc3\xa9morragique \xc3\xa0 Ebola se caract\xc3\xa9rise souvent par une brusque mont\xc3\xa9e de temp\xc3\xa9rature, avec une faiblesse intense, des myalgies, des c\xc3\xa9phal\xc3\xa9es et des maux de gorge. Cette fi\xc3\xa8vre est souvent suivie de vomissements, de diarrh\xc3\xa9es, d'\xc3\xa9ruptions cutan\xc3\xa9es, d'insuffisance r\xc3\xa9nale et h\xc3\xa9patique et d'h\xc3\xa9morragies internes et externes. Elle se transmet par contact direct avec le sang, les s\xc3\xa9cr\xc3\xa9tions, les organes ou des liquides biologiques des sujets infect\xc3\xa9s. Il n'existe aucun traitement ni vaccin sp\xc3\xa9cifiques pour la fi\xc3\xa8vre h\xc3\xa9morragique \xc3\xa0 virus \xc3\x89bola. Le r\xc3\xa9servoir naturel semble se trouver dans les for\xc3\xaats tropicales du continent africain et du Pacifique occidental. La fi\xc3\xa8vre h\xc3\xa9morragique \xc3\xa0 virus Ebola s'\xc3\xa9tait d\xc3\xa9j\xc3\xa0 d\xc3\xa9clar\xc3\xa9e dans la province Orientale en 1999 et en 2000. Elle s'\xc3\xa9tait d\xc3\xa9j\xc3\xa0 manifest\xc3\xa9e \xc3\xa0 l'Equateur en 1976 et en 1977, au Bandundu en 1995 et au Kasa\xc3\xaf Occidental en 2007 et en 2008. \n\xa0 \n Envoyer par email  ", "Province d'Orientale, DR Congo | Ebola | Humans"

' WHO rules out smallpox outbreak in eastern Uganda \nKAMPALA, March 25 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization (WHO) office here has ruled out an outbreak of smallpox in eastern Uganda after suspected cases were reported. \nJoaquim Saweka, WHO country representative, told Xinhua by telephone on Thursday that preliminary investigations show that the suspected cases may turn out to be chickenpox, which is common in the East African country. \n"It is not smallpox, most likely it is chickenpox and these are isolated cases without linkage. BIRD FLU: Bird Flu Detected in Nawalparasi, Nepal
'The Avian Influenza (H5N1) virus has been detected in Nawalparasi. The government had sent samples for test to UK laboratory some days back following death of chickens and ducks in the area.\n\nFollowing lab test results that confirmed bird flu, the local authorities have restricted transportation of the birds within 500 meters in Dheurali VDC of the district, some 8 km north of the east-west highway.\n\nLarge numbers of chicken and ducks have died in Jhyalbas, Guheri, Beluwa, Dihi and Ruksi villages. On 10 March 2010, her condition had worsened so she was transferred to Bach Mai Hospital where she is being provided with ventilation.   An epidemiological investigation showed that the patient had exposure to sick and dead poultry. Of the 116 cases confirmed to date in Viet Nam, 58 have been fatal. 16 Mar 2010
Avian Influenza
Gonzales County, Texas, United States
'29.450239','-97.483604',5,11008
BIRD FLU: Ducks Destroyed in Texas over Bird Flu Fears
'Around 3,500 ducks in Gonzales County had to be destroyed earlier this year by an order from state officials.\n\nThe ducks, owned by Gonzales resident Steve Hendershot, were located on County Road 238 north of Gonzales.\n\nThe Gonzales Inquirer has been working on this story for more than a month. State officials at first said they were unaware of the issue and refused any comment. However, after a phone call from the office of Rep. Edmund Kuempel, R-Seguin, officials released the entire story about what happened.\n\nState officials said the flock had to be destroyed because of positive tests for a bird virus.\n\nAndy Schwartz, state epidemiologist for the Texas Veterinary Medical Diagnostic Laboratory (TVMDL), said last week the situation began last November during random testing of the duck flock.\n\nSchwartz said new rules in the state require random testing of flocks when birds from those flocks are sold at live bird markets in Texas. Such was the case with the ducks in Gonzales County.\n\nHe said state officials did a "routine sampling" and those samples were sent to the diagnostic laboratory at Texas A&M University in College Station.\n\nSchwartz said when the tests were conducted, "it came up positive" for possible Avian flu virus. However, he also said that "any influenza will trip the test."\n\nBecause of the positive test, the samples were then sent to the National Veterinary Services facility in Ames, Iowa.\n\n"They repeated the same result and found the matrix positive," said Schwartz.\n\nAt that time, he said they "attempted to isolate the virus."\n\nSchwartz said more samples were then tested. They were "particularly concerned" about two strains which "could cause an outbreak in the poultry industry."\n\nThose two strains are H5 and H7, he said, and the samples tested negative for those two strains.\n\nAt that time, Schwartz said state officials "assessed the situation" and put the entire flock on a "hold order" until they got the results back.\n\n"We didn\'t have sick ducks," he said.\n\nOnce those results were received, Schwartz said the state "decided to allow controlled marketing where he (Hendershot) could move the live ducks to the markets in Houston."\n\nSchwartz said that Hendershot had two houses of birds. The first house had the positive test but he said the second house "continued to test negative for several months."\n\nHowever, in late December of last year, he said the state "got a positive" test on the second house.\n\n"We stopped movement of all birds," he said.\n\nWhat that meant, said Schwartz, was "we no longer let him send them to the market."\n\nSchwartz said the state felt "it was sort of a difficult situation. We didn\'t feel like we could stop it permanently."\n\nIt was at that time when the Texas Poultry Federation "agreed to come up with the money to buy out the flocks."\n\nOnce that happened, Schwartz said all of the ducks, somewhere in the neighborhood of 3,500, were "humanely destroyed."\n\nSchwartz said Hendershot was "having to feed the ducks and not able to market them."\n\nJames Grimm, executive vice president of the Texas Poultry Federation, confirmed last week they did enter into an agreement with Hendershot.\n\n"He had a concern about putting them down and we had a concern about them not being put down," said Grimm. "We came to a mutual agreement."\n\nDuring a luncheon last week, Dr. Tammy Beckham, director of the TVMDL, said there are eight million birds in the greater Gonzales area, making it the largest concentration of poultry in the state.\n\nGrimm said his group considers these situations "case by case," but that it is not uncommon for them to step in when necessary.\n\n"Any time if effects poultry we have a huge concern about it with all of the poultry in the Gonzales area," said Grimm.\n\nAsked if notices were sent to the major poultry producers in the county, Schwartz said that was done through the Texas Poultry Federation. That group, he said, likely notified the local poultry producers in the area.\n\nIt was known that a local poultry supply company had a mechanism in place where people had to disinfect their shoes before entering the building.\n\nSchwartz said poultry industry businesses are normally "urged to tighten their security" when a bird flu disease tests positive in an area.\n\nHe said the process for getting the ducks usually means the hatchlings are purchased from an out-of-state hatchery. Schwartz said he wasn\'t sure exactly how the birds were shipped but thinks they were flown into Austin and then picked up and brought to Gonzales County.\n\nSchwartz said the chicks are then grown locally before being taken to the various markets around the state. He said there are about 10 markets in Texas, most of them in the Houston area.\n\nHe said no fines are levied in cases like this, rather, the state is focused on trying "to stop the spread of disease."\n\nOnce the birds were destroyed, Schwartz said state officials then developed a "plot plan" for the location. That requires removal of the litter and requires cleaning of the houses "where the infected birds were."\n\nOnce that takes place, he said there is then a 30-day waiting period before any more birds can be placed in those houses.\n\nAs of last week, Schwartz said he was not sure if the cleaning and disinfectant had taken place. He did say the state has to be notified when it is completed.\n\n"I don\'t know if the 30-day clock has started," he said.\n\nSchwartz also said state officials were on the site after the virus was detected and continue to monitor the situation.\n\nHendershot is a former Gonzales city councilman and just recently filed as a candidate in the May election for another city council post.\n ', 'Gonzales County, Texas, United States | Avian Influenza | Humans'
http://c.moreover.com/click/here.pl?r2628205757

BIRD FLU: Bird Flu Spreading Fast in Parasi, Nepal
u'KATHMANDU: The government has been keeping the public in the dark despite the outbreak of bird flu in different parts of the country on the rise, it was learnt today.\n\nAround 500 backyard birds have died in Jhyalbas and Deurali VDCs of Nawalparasi district in the past few weeks.\n\nFollowing the outbreak, a team of veterinarians led by senior officer at the Animal Health Directorate (AHD), Dr Narayan Prasad Ghimire, was sent to the VDCs for a stamping out operation following verbal orders from Dr Ram Krishna Khatiwada, the programme director, AHD,yesterday.\n\nThe team comprised Dr Dayaram Chapagain of Department of Livestock Service (DLS), Chitwan, Dr Laxman Bahadur Dhakal, Chief of DLS Nawalparasi, Dr Damodar Neupane and a technician from the National Avian Laboratory, Chitwan.\n\nHowever, the team had to return from the VDCs without any job done as they failed to receive a written order from the Department of Livestock Services (DLS) to carry out the same. It is learnt that Dr Khatiwada had assured the team members of the written order from the centre. However, in the last hour, Dr Khatiwada directed the members to return.\n\nDr Khatiwada said that the report of the sample was not ready. \xe2\x80\x9cIt might come by Sunday evening,\xe2\x80\x9d he said.\n\nWhen asked about the team sent to the site, he said that was for the diagnosis and to make preparation for culling if the result was found to be positive. \xe2\x80\x9cWe need to prepare for several things including financial matters before culling the birds in order to maintain international norms,\xe2\x80\x9d he said.\n\nOne of the team members said the condition in those areas was \xe2\x80\x98horrible\xe2\x80\x99 as more birds are being infected and dying fast.\n\nSources said the birds of local resident Bal Bahadur Bakwal (Magar) of Jhyalbas tested positive for H5N1 virus in the central veterinary laboratory, Tripureswor.\n\nHowever, the authorities are reluctant to reveal the truth. As per the Bird Flu Control Order- 2064 BS, the government needs to declare \xe2\x80\x9cCrisis Zone\xe2\x80\x9d after a sample tests positive for H5N1 Avian virus either in the Central Veterinary Laboratory, Tripureswor or in any of the World Organisation for Animal Health reference laboratory. Nepal used to send the samples to the reference laboratory in Waybridge, London, for confirmation.\n\nThe government had earlier failed to declare the outbreak in Budhabare-Jhapa, Chainpur-8 in Chitwan, Buddhanagar in Rupandehi and Fultekra in Nepalgunj on time.\n\nIt may be noted that the authorities had revealed the outbreak only after The Himalayan Times reported that the government had been keeping the public in the dark.\n\nNepal Veterinary Association (NVA), Chitwan chapter, has condemned such act of the government and the DLS.\n\nIn a statement, the Chitwan chapter of NVA said that the department is being run in an \xe2\x80\x9cunethical manner\xe2\x80\x9d and at the cost of public health.\n\nThe government is once again trying to hide the outbreak of Bird flu in Nawalparasi district. ', 'Nepal | Avian Influenza | Humans'

Measles
Western Cape Province, South Africa
'-33.011436','20.614183',5,4335
Measles and diarrhoea death toll hits 16
' At least 16 children have died in the Western Cape in the recent measles and diarrhoea outbreaks that have put the province\'s health services under pressure. In February alone, nearly 900 children were admitted to hospitals across the province with diarrhoea. Of these, 395 were admitted to the Red Cross Children\'s Hospital. Health department spokeswoman Faiza Steyn said hospitals had brought in extra beds to cope with the diarrhoea outbreak - an annual occurrence in hot weather combined with poor sanitation. At least 765 cases of measles have been reported in the Western Cape since the outbreak in September. Steyn said eight measles deaths had been confirmed in the province by last Wednesday, while diarrhoea had also claimed eight lives. It was not clear when the diarrhoea outbreak had begun. To the medical fraternity, the summer months are known as the diarrhoea season. Heat encourages bacteria to breed, leading to serious gastric illnesses. In informal settlements, where there is poor sanitation, residents are particularly at risk of being affected by diarrhoea. The cases usually peak during February and March . Steyn said most children admitted to hospital with diarrhoea were from Delft, Mfuleni and Ikwezi, which is near the Helderberg drainage area. "We admitted almost 900 children in February. Most hospitals have opened extra beds to cope with the season, as we did last year. There have been increases in medical and nursing staff," she said. Last year, 37 city children under the age of five died of diarrhoea during February, March and April. In 2005, more than 100 children, most of them from poverty-stricken areas, died. Steyn said that because the measles outbreak coincided with the diarrhoea season, health services had been under significant and increased pressure due to an upsurge in patient numbers. She said diarrhoea, as one of the measles complications, could contribute to deaths associated with measles as well as those linked to pneumonia. The latest measles-related death was that of a one-year-old boy with TB complications, who died in Tygerberg Hospital\'s intensive care unit on Wednesday. Both Tygerberg and Somerset hospitals have special isolation wards to deal with serious measles cases. On Friday the Tygerberg ward had 15 patients, while Somerset Hospital had 31. ', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Measles | Humans', 'Western Cape Province, South Africa | Diarrhea | Humans'

Die Leitung der Heime Kriens empfiehlt, vorerst von Besuchen in den Heimen abzusehen, um eine weitere Ausbreitung des Virus zu verhindern. Organisation mondiale de la Sant\u00e9
4 Mar 2010
Avian Influenza
Dakahlia Governorate, Egypt
'30.916670','31.500000',5,4767
Avian influenza - situation in Egypt - update 31
u' Le premier est un homme de 53 ans du district de Shobra Elkhima, dans le Gouvernorat de Qaliobia. Les sympt\xf4mes sont apparus le 27 f\xe9vrier\xa0; il a \xe9t\xe9 hospitalis\xe9 le jour m\xeame et trait\xe9 \xe0 l\u2019oseltamivir. Il est dans un \xe9tat critique.  Le deuxi\xe8me est un petit gar\xe7on \xe2g\xe9 de 1 an, du district de Banha, dans le Gouvernorat de Qaliobia. Les sympt\xf4mes sont apparus le 22 f\xe9vrier\xa0; il a \xe9t\xe9 hospitalis\xe9 le 23 et trait\xe9 \xe0 l\u2019oseltamivir. Il est dans un \xe9tat stationnaire.  Le troisi\xe8me est un gar\xe7on de 10 ans, du district de Meet Ghamr, dans le Gouvernorat de Dakalia. Les sympt\xf4mes sont apparus le 10 f\xe9vrier\xa0; il a \xe9t\xe9 hospitalis\xe9 le 14 et trait\xe9 \xe0 l\u2019oseltamivir. Il est dans un \xe9tat de gravit\xe9 moyenne.  Le quatri\xe8me est une femme de 30 ans, du district de Kellin, dans le Gouvernorat de Kafr El-Sheik. Les sympt\xf4mes sont apparus le 10 f\xe9vrier\xa0; elle a \xe9t\xe9 hospitalis\xe9e le 11 et trait\xe9e \xe0 l\u2019oseltamivir. Elle est dans un \xe9tat stationnaire.  Le cinqui\xe8me est un gar\xe7on de 13 ans, du district de Kafr El-Sheik, dans le Gouvernorat de Kafr El-Sheik. Les sympt\xf4mes sont apparus le 10 f\xe9vrier\xa0; il a \xe9t\xe9 hospitalis\xe9 le 14 et trait\xe9 \xe0 l\u2019oseltamivir. Il est dans un \xe9tat stationnaire. 'Measles cases are increasing in Ireland, with 320 cases notified since August 2009. Nearly two-thirds of these cases (n=206) were unvaccinated. HM Community News Reports
4 Mar 2010
Chikungunya
Taiwan
'23.873001','121.016998',6,193
Taiwan records three cases of Chikungunya fever: CDC - The China Post
u' Updated\xa0Wednesday, March 3, 2010 9:50\xa0am\xa0TWN,\xa0CNA \n Taiwan records three cases of Chikungunya fever: CDC \n TAIPEI, Taiwan -- Taiwan recorded three cases of Chikungunya fever \xe2\x80\x94 all from Indonesia \xe2\x80\x94 in the first two months of this year, the Centers for Disease Control (CDC) said yesterday. \n The number of cases of the mosquito-borne disease is higher than in the same periods for 2008 and 2009, which each had a single case, according to CDC Deputy Director General Shih Wen-yih. Among the three cases registered this year was a 5-year-old boy, who contracted the disease when visiting relatives in Sumatra with his family, Shih said. The other two cases were a sailor who was infected in Jakarta, and a domestic helper who was infected in Surabaya, Shih said. All three cases were discovered through airport fever screenings. Shih said the situation indicates that the Chikungunya outbreak in Indonesia is very severe and he urged travelers to Indonesia and other Southeast Asian countries to take proper precautions against mosquito bites. Any traveler to Indonesia who experiences symptoms such as fever, headache, nausea and vomiting after returning home should seek medical attention immediately and inform their doctors of their travel history, Shih added. CDC statistics show that from October 2007 until the end of 2009, 20 cases of the disease were recorded in Taiwan, none of which were domestic. Nine out of the 20 cases were from Indonesia, while five were from Malaysia, the statistics indicate. The Chikungunya virus is transmitted to humans by a certain kind of virus-carrying mosquito. The disease affects the joints of the extremities and the pain associated with a Chikungunya infection can persist for weeks, months, or in some cases years. Other symptoms of the disease include intense headache, insomnia and an extreme degree of prostration. \n Infectious Diseases\xa0Breaking News  ', 'Taiwan | Chikungunya | Humans'
http://www.chinapost.com.tw/health/infectious-diseases/2010/03/03/246628/Taiwan-records.htm

Avian influenza &ndash; situation in Viet Nam - update 8
"  The first case is a 3 year-old female residing in Ninh Hoa District, Khanh Hoa Province. She developed symptoms on 27 January 2010, and was hospitalized at Ninh Hoa district hospital on 28 January. She is recovering well. The source of exposure is currently under investigation. Her family raises chickens but did not report any mass poultry illness or death. However, Ninh Hoa District and Van Ninh District are currently being monitored because of recent H5N1 poultry outbreaks.   The second case was a 38 year-old female residing in Cai Be District, Tien Giang Province. She developed symptoms on 13 February 2010. The patient was admitted to the Sa Dec Hospital in Dong Thap Province on 21 February where she died on 23 February. An epidemiological investigation showed that the patient had slaughtered and processed sick water fowl.   The third case is a 17 year-old female residing in Son Duong District, Tuyen Quang Province. She developed symptoms on 19 February 2010 and was taken to the Son Duong District General Hospital on 24 February where she is currently being treated for mild breathing difficulties. Approximately, 10 days ago, there were unexplained deaths of chicken in the patient's household. She participated in the disposal of the dead poultry.  Of the 115 cases confirmed to date in Viet Nam, 58 have been fatal. ", 'Vietnam | Avian Influenza | Humans'
